</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ugulorgularin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gulor Gularin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Been around a while</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(2/1/02 4:55:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=867.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: just a group of idiots</span><hr size=1> Instead of choosing the most extreme example in order to appear witty, try looking at the least extreme example. Before you can engage the mobs, you need to have a certain number of people present and organized into groups. In the case of the Grey, collecting this minimum amount of effective personnel can be done just as effectively just inside the Scarlet Desert zoneline as it is in the hallway in the Temple of Ssra. So you schedule your raid by saying &quot;meet at Scarlet Desert zoneline at x time&quot;. People show up as they usually do, in dribs and drabs. Once you have the minimum number of people you need, say 12 or so, you group them up, make sure they have some sort of EB, invis them and send them in. They take about 10 seconds or so to make it to the Temple of Ssra, maybe causing a train but maybe not. Your raid proceeds to the first targetted mob and begins the hunt. In the meantime late arrivals over and above your minimum start to arrive at the Scarlet Desert zoneline. They wait a few minutes until 3 or 4 of them are together, then they invis and head in to catch up to the main force. Overall you have not lost any significant time on your raid, you have minimized the chance of some of your weaker members getting bushwacked on the way in and shown some consideration for others hunting in the Grey. Does this sound ridiculous to you now?<br>
<br>
I have a few observations to make here:<br>
<br>
1. Everybody who has progressed past level 2 or so has created trains during their career.<br>
2. Everybody who has progressed past level 2 or so has been the victim of someone elses train during their career.<br>
3. Everybody mentioned above has bitched about being trained at sometime during their career.<br>
4. Nobody likes to train others except for a few select cretins who do it for fun until they get banned.<br>
5. When you are hunting near a zoneline in an agressive mob zone, you are going to get trained and should accept it as the price of hunting there. That being said, there is a difference between an acceptable amount of trains and a ridiculous amount. IMO 17 trains by 30 or so people falls under the ridiculous amount.<br>
6. The original poster did not raise the issue because he noticed a train or two in a couple hours. He raised it because the same guild was responsible for what he (and I) consider a preposterous number of trains. <br>
7. In each case, the trainer shouted warnings. Obviously the trains were not being done maliciously, but surely 17 out of 30 some odd invisibilities did not fail in the 10 seconds or so it takes to make the run. More likely they just made the dash with no preparation because they were in a hurry.<br>
<br>
I agree that it is possible to get all your people into the Temple individually without causing trains. It does take some attention to where the mobs are and timing however. I was asked, sarcastically, to give tips on how I would do things. I did so. Some people apparently think training the area is acceptable and not worth any effort on their part to avoid. I happen to disagree with that attitude. Please take my post in the spirit it is intended and not as a slam against ToV, Vision, or anyone else who happened to be hunting there that night. I try not to generalize about guilds, but I will point out cases where I think they can do better. I have pretty much said all I have to say on this subject...if any of you feel personally offended, my apologies. <p>Gulor Gularin
